{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 15:57:55.006253", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — Multi-tier Clos (EBGP) topology\n\nScope and method\n- Reviewed host reachability (pc_0_0 → pc_0_1 ping results).\n- Collected BGP RIB snapshots (frr_get_bgp_conf) and routing tables (frr_show_ip_route) from each FRR router in the topology: super_spine_router_0, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1.\n- Collected host network configuration for pc_0_0 and pc_0_1.\n- Focus: detect anomalies, localize faulty device(s), identify root-cause evidence from collected state.\n\nExecutive summary / overall health\n- The control plane (BGP) and data-plane (host-to-host connectivity) appear healthy and converged.\n- End-to-end host reachability: pc_0_0 → pc_0_1 shows 0% loss (4/4 pings successful, RTTs ~3.5 ms) — data-plane connectivity is functioning.\n- BGP is established and prefix distribution is complete: each leaf is advertising its /24 and the prefixes are present on spines and the super-spine.\n- No interfaces reported as down in the routing outputs, and connected subnets (/31 inter-router links and /24 host subnets) are present in each router's RIB.\n\nKey findings (detailed)\n\n1) Host-level reachability\n- pc_0_0: IP 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1 (host config shows eth0 up).\n- pc_0_1: IP 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1 (host config shows eth0 up).\n- Ping pc_0_0 → pc_0_1: 4 packets, 0% loss; RTT average ≈ 3.52 ms.\n\n2) BGP prefix propagation and route presence\n- leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200):\n  - Locally-originated prefix: 10.0.0.0/24 (originated, next-hop 0.0.0.0).\n  - Learns 10.0.1.0/24 via its spine neighbor (next-hop on the /31 link).\n- leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201):\n  - Locally-originated prefix: 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - Learns 10.0.0.0/24 via its spine neighbor.\n- spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) and spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101):\n  - Each spine has learned both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 (via the connected leaf links and via alternate paths).\n  - Next-hops seen in BGP are the directly-connected /31 neighbor addresses (expected for eBGP).\n- super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000):\n  - Receives both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 via both spine routers, showing multi-path visibility (redundancy distributed upward).\n\n3) Control-plane / routing table details\n- Per-router RIB observations (selected highlights):\n  - super_spine_router_0 routes:\n    - BGP entries for 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 with two paths (via 172.16.0.1 and 172.16.0.3) — two spines present as next-hops.\n  - spine_router_0_0 routes:\n    - BGP-selected routes to 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.5 (eth1).\n    - BGP-selected routes to 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7 (eth2).\n  - spine_router_0_1 routes:\n    - BGP-selected routes to 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.9 (eth1).\n    - BGP-selected routes to 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.11 (eth2).\n  - leaf routers show the expected connected /24s on their host-facing interfaces and BGP-learned remote /24s via their spine-facing /31 links.\n- No BGP session flaps or missing prefixes were observed in the captured RIB snapshots — all announced prefixes are visible where expected.\n\nAnomalies, suspicious observations, and behavioral notes\n- No functional anomalies detected:\n  - No packet loss between the two hosts.\n  - All /24 host prefixes are present throughout the EBGP network (leaf → spine → super-spine).\n  - Inter-router /31 links are present and shown as connected in each router's routing table.\n- Observed expected path asymmetry / path selection:\n  - Each prefix is present with multiple AS-path alternatives on upstream devices (e.g., the super-spine sees both spines advertising the same prefixes). The chosen next-hop differs per prefix and per spine, which naturally yields asymmetric forwarding depending on path selection. This is normal in EBGP multi-homing; it is a noteworthy operational characteristic (redundancy + asymmetric paths), not a fault.\n- Router ID notation:\n  - super_spine_router_0 shows router-id 172.16.0.0. Using an interface address ending with .0 as a router-id is unusual; not inherently an error but worth noting as a minor configuration quirk.\n- No evidence of:\n  - Missing BGP neighbors,\n  - Routes with unreachable next-hops,\n  - Interface shutdowns or link failures,\n  - Routing loops in the provided outputs.\n\nLocalization of potential problem sources\n- Since no outages or anomalies were detected in the control plane or data plane, there are no faulty devices to isolate from the provided data.\n- All devices present in the topology (super_spine_router_0, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1) show expected route advertisements and connected networks in their routing tables.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (for observed state)\n- The current state (BGP convergence, multiple next-hops, asymmetric selection) is consistent with the intended EBGP Clos design:\n  - Leaves originate their /24s (local next-hop 0.0.0.0).\n  - Spines receive leaf advertisements; spines peer with super-spine which receives both spine advertisements.\n  - The presence of multiple available AS-paths and differing route selection across spines leads to asymmetric forwarding paths — expected in the multi-path, multi-AS design. This is not a failure; it is the normal result of ECMP/route selection rules and the EBGP topology.\n- No misconfiguration or failed component was identified from the collected snapshots.\n\nSummary conclusion\n- Network condition: Healthy and converged. BGP advertisements for the host subnets are present throughout the network and hosts have end-to-end connectivity.\n- Abnormalities: None that affect reachability or BGP convergence were identified. Observed multi-path/asymmetric forwarding is expected behavior for the given EBGP Clos design.\n- Faulty devices: None identified based on the available data.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Pull per-device BGP neighbor status and session lifetime to confirm neighbor health (show bgp summary/vtysh output).\n- Dump interface IP assignments per router (if you want exact IP-to-interface mappings).\n- Run targeted traceroutes or additional pings to validate forwarding symmetry. \n\n(Report created from the following collected evidence: host ping results, per-router BGP RIB snapshots, per-router IP route outputs, and host network configurations.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 6901, "output_tokens": 6587, "total_tokens": 13488, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4928}}}
